Case Study of Cyclistic

About

Cyclistic is a bike-sharing company based in Chicago, IL. They offer several different types of passes: single-ride, full-day, or annual memberships. Casual riders are people who use either the single-ride pass or the full-day ride pass. Cyclystic members are the people with annual memberships.

Cyclistic would like to convert more casual riders to an annual membership for future growth and to maximize profits, however they need to know why people are choosing the different types of riding. To figure this out, they need to understand how people are using the bikes to better market the annual membership.

There are three questions they specifically want answered:
  1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
  2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?
  3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?

Since they all have the same variables and the same types for the variables, they can be combined to one dataset.

#Bind all dataframes to one dataframe
all2023 <- bind_rows(Jan2023, Feb2023, Mar2023, Apr2023, May2023, Jun2023, Jul2023, Aug2023, Sep2023, Oct2023, Nov2023, Dec2023)

Now the data can be cleaned further by removing extra spaces in the column names, making sure the data is the same format (no random capitalization).

#clean. remove spaces, etc.
all2023clean <- clean_names(all2023)

Now we want the start and end times to be in time format, not character

#Format started_at and ended_at as time
all2023clean$started_at <- as.POSIXct(all2023clean$started_at, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")
all2023clean$ended_at <- as.POSIXct(all2023clean$ended_at, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S")

To make sure this was done correctly, we can use str again, if the dates are now POSIXct format, it was done correctly

 $ end_lat           : num  41.9 41.8 42 41.8 41.8 ...
 $ end_lng           : num  -87.6 -87.6 -87.7 -87.6 -87.6 ...
 $ member_casual     : chr  "member" "member" "casual" "member" ...

With the start and end times in the correct format, we can now calculate the ride_length

#add ride_length column
all2023clean <- all2023clean %>%
  mutate(ride_length= ended_at - started_at)

We also want to have another column with the day of the week, using wday() and label=TRUE so the column will have the days of the week written out instead of numbers.

#add day_of_week column
all2023clean <- all2023clean %>%
  mutate(day_of_week=wday(started_at, label=TRUE))

As well as for the month, using the month() function with label=TRUE, so the column will be the month names instead of numbers.

#add the_month column
all2023clean <- all2023clean %>%
  mutate(the_month=month(started_at, label=TRUE))

We can also graph the hours that people ride during, but we would need separate columns for just the times each ride started. To simplify this, I am just getting the hour, because we don’t need an exact time, just a time of day.

#column for start_time and end_time
all2023clean <- all2023clean %>%
  mutate(start_time=started_at %>% hour)

all2023clean <- all2023clean %>%
  mutate(end_time=ended_at %>% hour)

Now we can write this new dataframe to a csv file to be used in Tableau or other applications.

write.csv(all2023clean, file="Cyclisticdata.csv")

Data calculations

Now we can use all of these new columns to calculate more data that will be useful for analysis.

The first things we are going to calculate is the average ride length for both casual riders and members.

all2023clean %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  summarise(mean(ride_length))
NA

This gives us:
casual 1693.5033 seconds or around 30 minutes
member 750.8116 seconds or around 12.5 minutes

This shows us that casual riders are using the bikes for longer periods of time than members.

    14. What does the data mean?

    1. In answer to the first question Cyclistic would like answered (How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?): Based on the data I would infer that casual riders are sightseers. They bike for longer periods of time, in areas with a lot of sightseeing. They ridership of casual riders also increases drastically during the summer months, when children are out of school and people tend to plan vacations. The most popular day of the week is also Saturday, which is a popular day to get out of the house and do activities because most people have the day off. I would also infer that members live in Chicago and use the bikes for their day to day living, like going to work or to the gym. They tend to bike for shorter periods of time and they tend to start near areas with a lot of houses or by businesses. The most popular days for biking are Tuesday-Thursday, which is when most people work.

    2. To answer the second question (Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?): There are a few reasons why I think casual riders would buy an annual membership instead of the casual ride pass. The first reason would be if it made the most sense financially. The second would be if there were extra incentives with an annual membership. If someone is only in the city for a short time, they probably won’t see the need to spend extra money on an annual pass if they wouldn’t use it. However, if there were changes made to the annual pass to make it more worth it for them, then they might consider it. One incentive would be access to guided tours, so they could explore different parts of the city. These could be access via their smartphone. Another incentive would be to have a minimum ride amount, where the pass will expire in a year or, if they haven’t ridden x number of times by that time, then it would be valid until they have ridden x number of times. They could also work with local businesses to provide discounts. Another incentive would be if they could get a discount off of the annual membership based on how many casual rides they’ve done. Sometimes, customers like to try something out before spending a lot of money.

    3. To answer the third question (How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members)? Digital media is everywhere. Advertisements online can go a long way. I think Cyclistic could use Instagram, TikTok, and YouTube ads to promote their bikes. A good incentive for casual riders would be to offer coupon codes through the advertisements. They should also make sure to include more advertisements near the popular biking areas. Another way is to use influencers to promote the bikes and the perks of an annual membership.

    Conclusion

    To conclude: Currently, casual riders tend to be tourists and ride longer periods of time in the areas with attractions. Members, tend to right for shorter periods of time and in areas with businesses and homes. To get more casual riders to become annual members, Cyclistic should use more advertisements in the popular tourists areas and through popular social media websites that offer discount codes, push the annual membership by including guided tours or coupons with the purchase, and have influencers showcase the bikes.
